narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Learned a lot about single-variable calculus.

I learned a lot about Calc II, including Taylor Series, Polar Coordinates, and Integration by Parts. I also learned how to self-study using the textbook and advocate for myself by going to office hours for help.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: There could be more clarity on what is expected to be known for exams, and the teaching style and structure could be modified for more practice.

I think that a strength of the course was that the content was very interesting, and what we would learn each day was clearly laid out in the syllabus with the corresponding chapters in the textbook, making it easier to study. However, we did end up falling behind sometimes, so maybe the pace of the curriculum could be adjusted to be a bit slower and more realistic.

Another strength of the course was the professor, who always tried to answer everyone's questions and make sure everyone understood the content.

this course sucks!!!!!!!!!!! and you're screwed if your TA is not a good teacher. you're better off not going to class and self-teaching the entire course if you want to get a decent grade. going to office hours and peer tutoring don't even help and you're just made to feel like you're stupid if you don't automatically grasp the material.
The pace is pretty quick with not a lot of room for retention of complex topics.
Strength: problem sets were pretty fun; they gave a lot of opportunities to learn material and study for exams. Weakness: it's not that engaging of a class; I mean, it's math.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, it's a good math credit that allows you to learn a lot.
I would recommend this course to another student who is interested in math, because the course is very well organized and interesting, and the professors are very helpful and engaging.
NOOOOOOOOOOO! unless you absolutely need to take it.
Yes, I think it is a good stepping stone for those looking to take more complex math classes and, in general, for those who like calculus.
Yes! However, if you've taken AP Calc BC already, don't bother taking this class. Just take 120 because you'll basically be learning the same stuff as in BC.
